  "market_context": "London session swept Asia highs, forming an up-close order block; price retraced into that zone during New York session, where analyst identified short-term highs, confirmed a long-term high, then anticipated drop to sell-side liquidity below.",
  "key_observation": "Price formed a long-term high after three short-term highs (including one at 08:30 NY open), and the analyst expected price to drop from that intermediate-term high into pre-identified sell-side liquidity rather than retest the zone.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Analyst identified London session sweep of Asia highs and marked the resulting up-close candle as an order block on the 60-minute chart.",
    "Step 2: Dropped to 5-minute chart and watched price retrace into the London order block zone during New York session, labeling multiple short-term highs (STH) near 17450.0, 17430.0, and 17410.0.",
    "Step 3: Confirmed the highest STH (17450.0) as the long-term high after a third short-term high formed on its right side.",
    "Step 4: Identified the next intermediate-term high after price swept two prior short-term highs and formed another short-term high to its right.",
    "Step 5: Anticipated price would drop from that intermediate-term high into sell-side liquidity (previously marked lows), which occurred as price declined sharply toward the earlier consolidation low."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price dropped from the intermediate-term high into sell-side liquidity as anticipated; no explicit trade entry or P&L stated, but the move matched the structural expectation.",
  "lessons": "When clean FVGs are absent, advanced market structure—using sequential short-term highs/lows to confirm long/intermediate-term levels—can identify high-probability reversal zones and draw-on-liquidity targets for entries.",
